	doi = {10.1109/ICKECS65700.2025.11035381},
	abstract = {Cross-project defect prediction ({CPDP}) utilizes data from multiple projects to address the scarcity of training data in software defect prediction, a crucial aspect of improving software quality. Within {CPDP}, heterogeneous defect prediction ({HDP}) focuses on the unique challenge of predicting software defects across projects with differing metric sets. Recent advances have highlighted the potential of mixed-project data to enhance {HDP}; however, significant challenges persist, particularly the detrimental effects of noisy data and the underutilization of unlabeled data. To mitigate these issues, we introduce a novel approach, Landmark-Based Domain Adaptation and Selective {PseudoLabeling} ({LDASP}). This method encompasses a dual strategy: aligning both marginal and conditional distributions via landmark-based domain adaptation, and enhancing data utility through a selective pseudo-labeling technique that progressively incorporates unlabeled data based on their predictive confidence. Our experimental setup, comprising 530 prediction combinations across 27 projects and four datasets, evaluates the effectiveness of {LDASP}. The results indicate substantial improvements, with increases in F1-score and Area Under the Curve ({AUC}) by 9.8– 20.2\% and 4.8–14.4\%, respectively, over existing baseline methods. Each component of {LDASP} the landmark adaptation and the pseudo-labeling strategy contributes significantly to these performance gains, demonstrating their potential in practical applications of heterogeneous defect prediction.},
